*my #metoo storyğŸ‘‡ğŸ»but firstâ€”> lets teach our boys to value women for their hearts and minds and not by their bodies.*- whoâ€™s with me?
..
..
recently in a therapy session (yes i go to therapy. #therapyiscool right @heytiffanyroe ? and if youâ€™re a mental health providerâ€”or anyoneâ€” you should go to therapy at least once in your life).
..
..
back to my story:
so i was processing some recent triggers (#emdrrocks btw) and some old memories came up. 
tbh i had completely forgotten these memories. they werenâ€™t lost, hidden, suppressed or unconscious, but they were definitely not something i focused on or worried about. in fact, i truly thought i was â€œoverâ€ it.
..
..
it was a memory from college when i was 19 yo and taken advantage of by a childhood friend of mine. i was not â€œrapedâ€ so i honestly never thought it was sexual assault. i talked about it with a few girlfriends after the fact and even confronted the guy directly and no one validated me.
..
..
my girlfriends said: â€œoh stefani is grownup now...â€ â€œooo how scandalousâ€... â€œoh stefani, heâ€™s totally into you.â€
..
..
the guy saidâ€” in not so many wordsâ€” â€œthis is normal, it happens all the time, donâ€™t even worry about it.â€ and a few more vulgar words that iâ€™ll refrain from sharing here.
..
..
sure, i didnâ€™t lose my virginity. i didnâ€™t even have â€œreal sex,â€ but now almost 13 yrs later, i know for a fact it was sexual assault. and it was traumatic for me. and he did take advantage of me. and it was not my fault. and no, it was not normal.
..
..
i bring this up bc you never know when triggers and painful memories strike. we canâ€™t always predict or prevent painful memories or experiences from rising to consciousness. ..
..
my goal as a therapist and psychiatrist is not to take your emotions and feelings away, but to help you feel discomfort and move past it. ..
..
for me, i have a lot of tools in my tool bag to help me through these random, unexpected sufferings, but most importantly is my faith in jesus christ.
i know he forgives all (and for the record, i forgive my â€œperpetratorâ€) and most paramount is:
he provides, through his grace, all that i need to make it through suffering so that i can be stronger. cont ğŸ‘‡ğŸ»

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

"for the first time in its 127-year history, the american psychological association has issued guidelines to help psychologists specifically address the issues of men and boys â€” and the document features a warning.
â€œtraditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit malesâ€™ psychological development, constrain their behavior, result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental health and physical health,â€ the report warns.

the new â€œguidelines for psychological practice with boys and menâ€ defines â€œmasculinity ideologyâ€ as â€œa particular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population, including: anti-femininity, violence, adventure, risk, achievement, and eschewal of the appearance of weakness.â€ the report links this ideology to homophobia, bullying, sexual harassment, and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s., they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate partner violence in the u.s., and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.

the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the report include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; "understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others"; and "reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide." apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a part, too. he recommended they let their boys know, â€œitâ€™s ok to not be ok all the time.â€'
--tim fitzsimons, @nbcnews

text:
this book is so good.
i struggled to get through it because there was so much there, and i often felt angry as i read it (is that #ironic or #poignant?). my favorite part was how #rebeccatraister gently excavates all the layers, complications and nuance of anger. yes, anger is necessary, and women need to allow themselves to feel and express anger. no, we should not let anger control us. yes, women have a right to be angry. no, that does not mean weâ€™re automatically virtuous. yes, men need to do better. yes, white women need to do better. no, that is not easy or simple. if we are not honest about the nuance of oppression, how sometimes women turn against each other, or against other marginalized people, or disagree about how to advocate, then we will be naÃ¯ve and easily stymied. letâ€™s put on our fiercest love and empathy and awareness and own our anger in healthy, productive ways.
.
.
.

text:
well, the internet has done it again. after finding the old kevin hart tweets from 10 years ago, the ~investigators~ moved on to find more dirt, and they found some on gordon ramsay.
.

this is internet-clip editing at it's finest. it wasnâ€™t this bad!!! during an interview back in 2010 on the tonight show with jay leno, ramsay flirted (or harassed?) sofia vergara. the whole thing started when sofia yelled at both leno and ramsay for cooking her disgusting food. it was part of a skit.
.

after the skit was over, sofia said, â€œi never scream like that in real life,â€ and ramsay responded to her comment by touching her arm and saying, â€œonly in the bedroom?â€
.

vergara moved away from ramsay and looked a little annoyed by his comment. from there, ramsay continued to try his best to turn the conversation sexual. she shared a photo of herself eating pizza during a recent vacation, and ramsay was shocked by how she stuck the whole slice in her mouth.
. â€œyou had a whole wedge in your mouth at one time? you havenâ€™t heard of a knife and fork? you just pick it up and stick it in?â€
.

vergara did the thing women are â€œsupposedâ€ to do when theyâ€™re uncomfortable, she laughed and tried to change the subject. at the end of the interview, ramsay jumped in her chair. it was certainly strange, and ramsay definitely acted like a horny teenager, but iâ€™m not sure there is anything ~more~ to it.
.

i mean, people online are acting like heâ€™s the devilâ€¦swipe for some comments
.
.

this looks way worse then it really is.  the full clip shows her feeding him with her spoon, touching him back and clear flirtation.  don't believe the hype.  you can watch the full clip - hit he link in my bio. .
.

text:
1. the girls who shared their stories are victims! they never expected they would be held captive by literal and figurative walls.
2. grooming was a key component to luring the girls in. he saw a need, a vulnerability, or desire and he exploited it. he was methodical and calculating, so the girls mistook the grooming process as him being legitimately charming, interested in them, and genuine about his promises. slowly boundaries were crossed and abuse was initiated until it fully manifested.
3. mind control is real. these girls never expected they would be in a situation where they had to ask to eat, go to the bathroom, be subjected to physical violence, or denied access to their family.
4. shame kept them compliant in different ways. they believed they couldn't return home after disobeying or disrespecting their families. they had been forced to participate in vile acts that they thought would be exposed if they left. they had endured significant trauma and they were being told it was their fault.
5. kelly bragged about his actions in his music, but society overlooked it. also, there is no separating the man from the music. #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate #volunteer #family @officialmuterkelly

text: metoo was found on the street, a stray dog abandoned with her puppies that were never to be found. after painful months trying to get her out of the streets a couple was finally able to catch her. they posted her profile & story online and when i read it i knew i had to keep her so i drove almost 2h with my sister, mom and brother-in-law to take her back home with me. at 1st, she had her eye still. we assumed she was 1&1/2yo at the time and by what the vet said she must had been pregnant 3 times, so if you do the math she basically was pregnant all the time. it would have been a litter after another litter. she was very thin, ribs showing, and had a hard time trusting me. it took her a whole year to play with toys, jumping in the sofa or sleeping with me in the bed. she was also very sick when i got her. her eye was infected, the vet said it was for sure someone who spanked her, her previous owner if she had one, or someone mean while she was wandering in the streets. the eye had to be removed because she got blind. she was very happy after the eye removal and it was the 1st time i saw her running! sadly, this dog has been in and out the vet for her entire life. a couple of months after the eye surgery she also had to remove her uterus due to an infection caused by so many pregnancies. she had a lot of stomach and intestines problems and i was doing my very best to provide for her. i still don't know until this day how i was able to pull it off by living on a minimum wage, alone, with rent and bills to pay. i remember that i used no electricity whatsoever, i did not watch tv, etc. so i could provide for her. i worked 8h a day, somedays i stayed until long hours but never got payed for my extra labour. still i never failed to give her medicine at the due time. i don't know how i did it but i have done it. this dog is my child, my entire family. and i love her more than i can put into words. it was all worthwhile. nowadays, it is not just me, i live with my boyfriend for over 2 years now and we adopted a cat too! so when she recently had to remove her spleen it was easier to overcome. and no matter what stands in the way, we can get through it with love. ğŸ¶â¤

text:
6. it took an entire support system to pull off this type of ongoing abuse of multiple victims simultaneously. people were either directly participating in the abuse or were willing to turn a blind eye for a check.
7. you can't bargain with or think you're going to outwit a predator. they don't possess empathy, use rational thought processes, or experience fear of getting caught. in fact, many are outright sociopaths so we can't even begin to understand the depths of their depravity.
8. predators simply need access and opportunity. a few minutes is long enough to lure a victim in, and is certainly enough time to sexually abuse a victim.
9. don't judge these girls so harshly because no one can say with assurance exactly how they would respond if they found themselves in the grasp of a predacious monsters like r kelly.
10. black girls matter. while abuse occurs across every race, religious, and socioeconomic background, there is no way all of these girls should have been victimized by a public figure and in such public ways and there was nothing done to stop it. #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate #volunteer #family @officialmuterkelly

text:
>>> it's friday!!! <<<
.
.
surviving r. kelly...
.
.
as a social worker and survivor, it was rough writing this, rough watching 'surviving r. kelly', but even more rough hearing and seeing all of the victim blaming.
.
.
as a young girl who experienced the manipulation of several older guys who preyed on my pain, desperation, and vulnerability, i can personally say it's not okay to make statements such as, "she shouldn't have been being fast" or any of the other ridiculous comments i've witnessed. as a child, no one usually desires to just give up their childhood unless undesirable or traumatic things happen.
.
.
for me it was not having my dad around during my vital years, and being prematurely exposed to sex by way of molestation then hanging with the wrong crowds. that led to drugs, alcohol, stripping, promiscuity, and many other internal things. what made it worse was that because i was a young black girl, i was just written off as "fast", "good for nothing but laying on my back", and many other hurtful things. (god has since restored my relationship with my dad and he's literally my best friend).
.
.
as a woman who stayed in an abusive relationship for almost 2 years and was almost murdered by him, i can personally say it's not as easy as you think to "just leave" and it hurts to hear things such as, "she's stupid", "she's dumb", "i  would've been left", and any other ignorant and insensitive thing i've heard. if you've never been in that situation you don't know what you "would've" done.
.
.
when in any kind of abusive relationship, the victim usually blames self and holds onto the hope that they can change the abuser. manipulation is the foundation of the relationship in every aspect. the dysfunction becomes normal and anything outside of it is unfamiliar, thus scary. the victim's have usually already been isolated from their loved ones and been drilled that their abuser is the only person they have.
.
.
regardless of how "fast" or "mature" any of those girls were, r. kelly was an adult! which means he needs to be held accountable as well as those who helped him. my prayers go out to everyone who was affected. ğŸ˜”ğŸ™ğŸ½

text:
there are times when it can be really hard to get out of bed, to look forward to the day with a sense of excitement and possibility. life experiences may seem bleak but do you notice how you still get up? on those days, please acknowledge the choice you made to still keep going. celebrate the little things that no-one notices. there's no shame, no guilt, no arrogance - just a heart-centred gratitude that you made it up, and through another day x 
are you proud of you?

#mentalhealth #lifeistoday #celebrateyou #loveoverfearalways #perseverance

text:
yesterday i was at family court, i'd put in an application that would provide an extra layer of protection for me and my daughter. because i'm not eligible for legal aid, this meant i needed to represent myself, which is scary and stressful but if you are well prepared, manageable.

so the #narc was allowed to be present at the hearing via video link, this was the first time i'd seen him in 18 months (the last time was at the rape trial) and the only downside to representing myself is that i had to cross examine him, and he was allowed to cross examine me. 
the last time i spoke to him was nearly 3 years ago, when he broke into my home and attacked me. as you can imagine i was so nervous but you know what, when i saw him i felt nothing, no fear, anger, hate, remorse, guilt, sorrow, love, just nothing!

with everything i have learnt i was able to see him for what he was, an empty vessel, one that held no power over me. 
i'm sharing this experience because i want you to know that you can heal and you can free yourself from the hold they have over you.

ps. i also won the case ğŸ˜€
.
.
.

selalu ada hal2 baru yg akan kita pelajari dan temui ketika kita terus bergerak dan melawan.
.
.
how we define consent? besok, 18.30 di kenobi space kemang! .
.
#repost @infoscreening (@get_repost)
ãƒ»ãƒ»ãƒ»
under the spirit of #metoo, we highlighted the case of sexual violence that is still prevalent in today's society, particularly towards girls and women. with that in mind, almost unanimously, we understood the importance of consent in sexual activities.

but, is consent enough? in 2018 we saw worrying trend of misusing the concept of consent in dealing with sexual violence cases. almost exactly one year ago, we witnessed the entire aziz ansari fiasco with an anonymous woman's account accusing him of sexual violence. in ansari's defense, the act had been consensual. late 2018, irish feminists went enraged as a rape victim's underwear was produced in court as a proof that she'd consented to the harm done to her. of course, we haven't even delved further into the case of agni from ugm and the fact that there are still people who believe that she somewhat must have wanted it.

it is timely that now we have an open discussion about what consent is and more importantly, what it is not. surely, it is not a justification for rape. let's discuss further in our event below:

the poem, this  happens  with  every  girl : "me - too'' by gurjot s. kaler ,
is a heartfelt tribute to the millions of women in the world who suffer in  silence and are a victim of sexual harassment-cum-exploitation at every stage of their lives. indeed, it is actually a heartrending reality and a matter of grave concern to note that everyday,  innumerable women are raped, molested, eve-teased and sexually assaulted across the globe. 
the tragic truth is that every women has undergone the pain of sexual violence and faced some sort of sexual abuse during their lifetime, either directly or indirectly. 
the question which really begs for an answer is that whenever any kind of sexual crime happens with women, why are we all silent as the members of society ? don't we all have any moral and social responsibility to stand upright and defend our women's honor, prestige and integrity ? 
why do we refuse to raise our voice ? are we also waiting for that one day when our own mothers, sisters, wives and daughters will come home after becoming victims of sexual harassment and say that, "this happened with me-too". do not suffer in silence. raise your voice before it is too late. the world suffers a lot, not because of the violence of bad people but because of the silence of good people. be the change you wish to see in the world. 
the time has come to realize that we must gather the required courage to support, respect and protect our women as well as ensure their safety, security and survival at any cost.  therefore, "me-too'' is not a mere hashtag, its a global movement in support of women and is meant to  inspire them to raise their suppressed voices against all sorts of injustice in society. 
respect her - support her - protect her.

https://www.facebook.com/gurjot.s.kaler

https://www.instagram.com/gurjot.s.kaler

text:
a few months later, in autumn 2013, wylie met steve bannon. at the time, he was editor-in-chief of breitbart, which he had brought to britain to support his friend nigel farage in his mission to take britain out of the european union.

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. heâ€™s the only straight man iâ€™ve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

wylie meeting bannon was the moment petrol was poured on a flickering flame. wylie lives for ideas. he speaks 19 to the dozen for hours at a time. he had a theory to prove. and at the time, this was a purely intellectual problem. politics was like fashion, he told bannon.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text: so many talents in one frame. so, i am late to this but i just watched the entire episode a few days ago. so sad that rani got trolled for this. so now here are my thoughts... i think raniâ€™s opinions on the #metoo movement came in good context, but unfortunately was misinterpreted very negatively. deepika made some valid counter points. and though i agreed with raniâ€™s points, it cannot be the case in every scenario. some women donâ€™t have that strength or will power and not all women can learn martial arts. her views came out to be distorted and hence was super unpopular with the audience/viewers. in regards to her â€œbutting inâ€ every convo. well, yeah she did but so did others. not all, but some. some just like to talk a lot, some just stay quiet unless directly asked. i do agree rani has changed as a person, but also most people do after marriage. this was overall a fun episode and i absolutely love @deepikapadukone & @anushkasharma as actresses! so much talent. @tabutiful & @taapsee were good too. not a huge @aliaabhatt fan, but enjoyed her in this episode overall a fun filled episode. just sad that it didnâ€™t go well for rani.. oh well. #ranimukerji #ranimukherjee #ranimukherji #deepikapadukone #aliabhatt #tabu #taapseepannu #anushkasharma #roundtable #rajeevmasand

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the companyâ€™s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when youâ€™re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a personâ€™s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the â€œtraining setâ€ refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your â€œfeature setâ€: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, itâ€™s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data â€“ the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that youâ€™re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

text:
- she [rebekah mercer] loved me. she was like, oh we need more of your type on our side!

your type? - the gays. she loved the gays. so did steve [bannon]. he saw us as early adopters. he figured, if you can get the gays on board, everyone else will follow. itâ€™s why he was so into the whole milo [yiannopoulos] thing.

robert mercer was a pioneer in ai and machine translation. he helped invent algorithmic trading â€“ which replaced hedge fund managers with computer programs â€“ and he listened to wylieâ€™s pitch. it was for a new kind of political message-targeting based on an influential and groundbreaking 2014 paper researched at cambridgeâ€™s psychometrics centre, called: - computer-based personality judgments are more accurate than those made by humans. - in politics, the money man is usually the dumbest person in the room. whereas itâ€™s the opposite way around with mercer, says wylie. - he said very little, but he really listened. he wanted to understand the science. and he wanted proof that it worked.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

@sagelyspoken 
krachtig, prachtig, levend in haar waarheid en wandelend in haar doel.
dat zijn de woorden die romaina nu zal gebruiken. voorheen zou dit zijn geweest: â€œzwak, lelijk, vervloekt en verdwaald.

een 30 jarige vrouw met ghanees en burkinees roots. als ervaringsdeskindige en oprichtster van â€˜through the eyes of sageâ€™ focust zij op taboos binnen de donker gemeenschap zoals: depressie, seksueel misbruik en veel meer. haar doel is uiteindelijk om cyclussen te verbreken door deze dingen bespreekbaar te maken, heling te ondergaan zodat wij die beter weten ook beter kunnen.

nu is de tijd om in dialoog te gaan met elkaar, eerlijk en unfiltered en voorkomen dat we bloeden op mensen die ons niet hebben/hadden gesneden.â€ wil je meer over haar reis en wombstory horen! kom en laat je inspireren!

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
footage of nigel farage swigging a pint and thanking steve bannon and breitbart for the brexit result was deleted from a breitbart youtube channel, following the data scandal surrounding cambridge analytica. - well done bannon, well done breitbart, the ex-ukip leader announces in the short clip. - you helped with this. hugely.

farageâ€™s nod to steve bannon certainly hasnâ€™t aged well in the context of the recent storm around cambridge analyticaâ€™s influence over the eu referendum.

it was revealed that data from 50 million facebook profiles were looked at against the electoral register, and then used to build an algorithm which analyses peopleâ€™s personality traits in relation to their voting behaviour.

this data could then be used to find potential swing voters and create messages tailored to influence them politically.

the firmâ€™s vice president at the time was steve bannon, who was also head of the right-wing website breitbart and was running donald trumpâ€™s campaign to become us president.

anna o'donohue

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the effos made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to cou documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the cou documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf
medium

text:
born and raised in this city, paris. early on, i had to interact with a lot of tourists working as a waitress in the touristic areas, who could only speak english or chinese! all seemed to be so amazed by this city, its architecture, the beautiful bridges, the lights, the eiffel tower that i remember climbing for the first time in my early 20s when an american/dominican friend @ecyrnomads came to paris to stay with me! remember this?! you basically forced me to go up, because really i couldnâ€™t be bothered! all i wanted to do was to get out of here!! travel the world and go where all these people came from! âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨
2019 - i have now visited 5 continents and 49 countries (and islands) so far, and thatâ€™s only 20% of planet! (maybe i could have reached 50% if i had stopped going back to the same places!)ğŸ¤¦ğŸ¾â€â™€ï¸
anyway! after travelling abroad, i now see and enjoy the beauty of paris but mostly the food, the bread, the cheese and the wine! ğŸ¥– ğŸ· ğŸ¾ ğŸ§€ still not saying itâ€™s the best city in the world (to me) but it is a very beautiful city, definitely worth visiting. have you been to paris? âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn
